import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Base
  title="01 · Concept Note — Interphase"
  current="01 · Concept Note"
  next={{ href: `${base}/02-metaphor`, num: '02', title: 'The Biological Metaphor' }}
>
  <!-- COVER -->
  <section class="cover">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow cover-eyebrow">01 · Positioning & Market</p>
      <h1>The missing<br /><em>infrastructure</em><br />for change.</h1>
      <p class="cover-sub">
        Interphase is not a change management tool. It is the preparatory
        environment that makes change possible — the biological necessity that
        organisations have been skipping for decades.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE PROBLEM -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The problem</p>
        <h2>Why <em>70%</em> of transformations fail</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">The change management industry exists because organisations know change is hard. The paradox: most change management solutions are themselves part of the problem.</p>
          <p>Traditional change management is event-based. A consultant is brought in, a programme is run, the consultant leaves. What remains is an organisation that has been <em>managed through</em> change — but not equipped to undergo it. It is like performing surgery without anaesthetic: it works, but it damages the organism in ways that compound over time.</p>
          <p>What is missing is not a better consultant or a shinier tool. What is missing is <strong>infrastructure</strong> — a continuous, ambient layer of organisational self-awareness that allows change to be absorbed, processed, and metabolised rather than simply announced and then endured.</p>

          <div class="stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">70<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">Of all organisational transformations fail</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">72<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">Of failures caused by resistance & inadequate support</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">38<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">Of employees willing to support change today — down from 74% in 2016</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">96<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">Of organisations in some active phase of change at any given time</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>These numbers reveal a structural gap, not a human one. People are not becoming more resistant. They are not being prepared. That preparation gap is what Interphase fills — continuously, scalably, and at the level of the individual.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE CONCEPT -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The concept</p>
        <h2>Cultural Architecture, <em>not change management</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"We are not building a change management platform. We are building the missing phase that makes change biologically possible."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Interphase — Core Positioning</div>
          </div>

          <p>In biology, a cell cannot divide without completing Interphase: a period of growth, metabolic activity, and internal replication. Rush it, and the resulting cells are fragile, mutated, destructive. Organisations do exactly this — they impose restructurings, M&amp;A integrations, ESG rollouts, and leadership successions without the corresponding internal preparation.</p>

          <p>Interphase is <strong>Cultural Architecture</strong> — persistent infrastructure that prepares organisations to absorb transformation rather than merely manage it. The AI engine does not deliver answers. It generates the right questions, helping each person map their own path through the friction. Chaperones — human practitioners embedded in the platform — use real-time, anonymised data to guide targeted capacity-building sessions at precisely the right moment.</p>

          <h3>Four biological layers</h3>
          <p><strong>Nucleus</strong> — Individual reflection and transparency. The AI-powered conversation layer where each person reflects privately on their experience of change.</p>
          <p><strong>Cytoplasm</strong> — Chaperone-guided capacity building. The professional services layer, driven by anonymised data from the Nucleus.</p>
          <p><strong>Metabolic</strong> — Data-driven learning modules deployed in real time. Content that arrives when the organisation's data signals a specific readiness gap.</p>
          <p><strong>Organism</strong> — Collective evolution. The self-sustaining state where the organisation has internalised the capacity to process change without continuous external support.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MARKET -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Market sizing</p>
        <h2>Three converging markets, <em>one unoccupied gap</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase sits at the intersection of three double-digit-growth markets — all currently underserved at the cultural-infrastructure layer.</p>

          <div class="tiles">
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>OCM Software</h4>
              <div class="big">$4.2B</div>
              <p>Growing to $17.2B by 2034 at 16.9% CAGR. Dominated by IT-change tooling; human layer almost entirely absent.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Employee Engagement</h4>
              <div class="big">$1.1B</div>
              <p>Growing to $3.15B by 2034 at 16.2% CAGR. Current tools measure sentiment; Interphase builds capacity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Employee Experience</h4>
              <div class="big">$6.7B</div>
              <p>Growing to $12.9B by 2035. No player focused on transformation-specific experience infrastructure.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Combined TAM</h4>
              <div class="big">~$12B</div>
              <p>Conservative 2025 total across the three markets. The cross-market position creates a defensible niche within a massive opportunity.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Why now.</strong> Three forces converge simultaneously: AI adoption is forcing the most significant cultural shifts in decades. Employee willingness to support change has collapsed from 74% to 38% since 2016. And AI-powered coaching has reached the maturity that makes the Chaperone model viable at scale for the first time.</p>
          <p><strong>Beachhead market.</strong> Mid-market European enterprises of 250–5,000 employees undergoing a defined transformation trigger — M&amp;A, ESG mandate, leadership succession, or digital rollout. Too complex for informal culture management, too resource-constrained for McKinsey-scale consulting, too people-centric to trust pure SaaS tooling.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMPETITIVE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Competitive positioning</p>
        <h2>The infrastructure layer <em>nobody owns</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>Interphase does not compete with change management consultancies or engagement platforms. It becomes the infrastructure layer that both require to deliver their work.</p>

          <div class="compare">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <h3>What exists today</h3>
              <div class="compare-item">McKinsey / BCG / Prosci — event-based consulting, expensive, extractive, no continuous layer</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Culture Amp / Lattice — measure engagement, do not build capacity</div>
              <div class="compare-item">ServiceNow / Jira — IT change management, treats humans as workflow objects</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Generic LMS — top-down content delivery, no real-time contextualisation</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Wellbeing apps — individual wellness, disconnected from organisational change</div>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col us">
              <h3>Interphase</h3>
              <div class="compare-item">Continuous, ambient infrastructure — not a project, not a programme, not a survey</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Builds individual and collective capacity, not just measures it</div>
              <div class="compare-item">AI generates questions, not answers — preserves human agency</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Real-time anonymised data drives Chaperone intervention at the exact right moment</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Measurable ROI: reduction in burnout, churn, and resistance</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>The strategic moat.</strong> As organisations use Interphase across multiple transformation cycles, the platform accumulates a richly contextualised picture of how that specific culture processes change. This data is invisible to competitors and deeply sticky for clients.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- REVENUE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Revenue architecture</p>
        <h2>Three-layer model, <em>each reinforcing the next</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Layer</th>
                <th>Model</th>
                <th>Unit economics</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Platform (SaaS)</strong></td>
                <td>Annual subscription per seat. Core Nucleus + Metabolic access. Per-seat pricing scales linearly with organisation size.</td>
                <td><span class="num">€8–18</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">per seat / month</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Chaperone Network</strong></td>
                <td>Revenue share on session fees plus annual certification. Practitioners become a go-to-market channel, bringing their existing client base to the platform.</td>
                <td><span class="num">30–40%</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">rev share + €2,400/yr cert</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Module Marketplace</strong></td>
                <td>Pre-built learning modules licensed per deployment. Organisations can access specific content without full Chaperone engagement.</td>
                <td><span class="num">€500–2,500</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">per deployment</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Lens Licensing</strong></td>
                <td>The AI interpretive framework licensed to specific verticals or platforms (OSCC, Soul.com). Same engine, different lens.</td>
                <td><span class="num">€50k–200k</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">/yr white-label</span></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>A 500-person company at €12/seat/month represents €72,000 ARR before any Chaperone sessions. The same Chaperone network can serve 40 such companies — generating €2.88M ARR from the platform layer alone.</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Illustrative unit economics — not guaranteed projections</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
